{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"56627921-e62e-477e-9b56-4382b3b55214","content":"In .NET MAUI, you use the **lifecycle events API** in `CreateMauiApp()` to hook into platform-specific events:\n\n```csharp\npublic static MauiApp CreateMauiApp()\n{\n    var builder = MauiApp.CreateBuilder();\n    builder.UseMauiApp<App>();\n\n    builder.ConfigureLifecycleEvents(events =>\n    {\n#if ANDROID\n        events.AddAndroid(android => android\n            .OnPause(activity => { /* runs on Android pause */ })\n            .OnStop(activity =>  { /* runs on Android stop  */ }));\n#endif\n\n#if IOS\n        events.AddiOS(ios => ios\n            .DidEnterBackground(app => { /* runs on iOS background */ }));\n#endif\n    });\n\n    return builder.Build();\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- Add `using Microsoft.Maui.LifecycleEvents;`\n- Use `#if ANDROID` / `#if IOS` preprocessor directives to keep platform code separate.\n- Each platform exposes its native events (e.g., `OnResume`, `OnDestroy`, `WillTerminate`, etc.).\n- You can register multiple handlers for the same event; they fire in registration order.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"6ea73637-f162-42ee-b808-0d7e4d5d3eb7","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about how to hook into platform-specific lifecycle events in .NET MAUI. This is a general knowledge question about .NET MAUI development — I can answer this directly without needing to search any codebase.","outputTokens":371,"requestId":"9825:1A0B9E:15BEBA3:184EF60:6A051E77"},"id":"901cc5ab-92ca-4d00-88e4-6f76daf3e659","timestamp":"2026-05-14T00:59:43.442Z","parentId":"8ca42714-4457-4e79-8d1d-c4af2a4ff46f"}
